---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} article={true} keywords="NC preneed 2026, North Carolina preneed market, preneed trends, funeral home strategy, NC funeral industry">
	<section class="bg-warm-white pt-24 pb-8 md:pt-32 md:pb-12">
		<div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
			<h1 class="font-heading text-3xl md:text-[40px] font-bold text-charcoal-900 leading-tight mb-4">
				The State of Preneed in North Carolina &mdash; 2026
			</h1>
			<p class="text-charcoal-500 mb-2">By <strong class="text-charcoal-900">Duane Cutlip</strong>, Licensed Preneed Funeral Director | March 2026</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
		<Breadcrumbs items={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'Insights', href: '/insights' }, { label: 'State of Preneed 2026' }]} />

		<article class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700">

			<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
				The preneed funeral insurance market in North Carolina is at an inflection point. A wave of demographic shifts, regulatory changes, carrier consolidation, and digital transformation is reshaping how funeral homes acquire and serve preneed clients. For independent funeral homes in North Carolina, the next five years represent both the greatest opportunity and the greatest risk in a generation.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				This report draws on national industry data, state-level regulatory developments, and nearly nearly two decades of on-the-ground experience selling preneed insurance across North Carolina. It's written for funeral directors, preneed managers, and owners who want to understand where the market is heading — and how to position their businesses to thrive.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Market Overview: A Growing but Underserved Market</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The U.S. funeral services market was valued at approximately $65.4 billion in 2025 and is projected to grow at a 5.2% compound annual growth rate (CAGR) through 2030. Within that, preneed insurance represents one of the fastest-growing segments, with a 19% increase in prepaid funeral plan participation nationally over the past five years.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				North Carolina is home to more than 750 licensed funeral establishments serving a population of over 10 million — and that population is aging rapidly. Yet despite this scale, the state remains underserved by dedicated, local preneed expertise. Most preneed sales are still handled by funeral home staff who wear multiple hats, or by large national carriers with little understanding of local market dynamics.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				This gap is an opportunity. Funeral homes that invest in their preneed programs now — with trained staff, compliant processes, and carrier-agnostic guidance — will lock in market share that compounds over decades.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Cremation Trends: The North Carolina Are Different</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Nationally, the cremation rate reached 63.4% in 2025, and it continues to climb. The Cremation Association of North America (CANA) projects it will reach 80% by 2040. For many in the industry, this trend feels like an existential threat to preneed revenue.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				But North Carolina tells a different story. North Carolina's cremation rate sits around 55-60%. Cultural factors — strong religious communities, multigenerational family ties, and traditional burial preferences — keep North Carolina meaningfully below the national average.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				What does this mean for preneed? <strong>Higher preneed value per policy.</strong> Traditional burial services carry a higher price point than cremation, which means the average face amount on a preneed policy in North Carolina remains higher than in states where cremation dominates. A family choosing a traditional funeral in North Carolina is looking at $8,000 to $12,000 or more in total costs — all of which can be covered under an Inflation Proof Guarantee through a preneed policy.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The takeaway: funeral homes in North Carolina still have a significant traditional burial market to serve, and preneed is the vehicle to capture that revenue in advance. The cremation shift is coming, but it's arriving more slowly here, giving funeral homes a window to build robust preneed programs before the economics change.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Carrier Landscape: Global Atlantic, SCI, and the Independent Squeeze</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The preneed insurance carrier landscape is consolidating, and the implications for independent funeral homes are significant. The most notable development has been the deepening partnership between Global Atlantic Financial Group and Service Corporation International (SCI), the world's largest funeral services company.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				SCI's scale gives it negotiating power with carriers that independent funeral homes simply can't match. As Global Atlantic and SCI strengthen their relationship, smaller funeral homes may find that the carriers they've relied on are increasingly optimizing their products, commissions, and support structures for the large corporate funeral home chains.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				This doesn't mean independents are locked out — but it means they need to be smarter about carrier selection. Funeral homes that work with a single carrier are particularly vulnerable. If that carrier shifts its focus, raises rates, or changes commission structures, the funeral home has no alternative.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				<strong>The solution is carrier-agnostic preneed advising.</strong> Working with a licensed preneed professional who represents multiple carriers — and who understands the strengths and limitations of each — protects the funeral home from dependency on any single product line. It also ensures families get the best available product for their specific situation, which reduces cancellations and increases satisfaction.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Prepaid Plan Growth: 19% and Accelerating</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				One of the most encouraging data points in the industry is the 19% growth in prepaid funeral plan participation nationally over the past five years. This growth is driven by several converging factors:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-6">
				<li><strong>Consumer awareness:</strong> Media coverage of rising funeral costs and the financial burden on surviving families has increased significantly.</li>
				<li><strong>Financial literacy:</strong> More Americans are integrating funeral planning into their broader financial and estate planning.</li>
				<li><strong>Medicaid planning:</strong> Irrevocable preneed contracts remain one of the most reliable ways to protect assets while qualifying for Medicaid — a critical consideration for the aging population.</li>
				<li><strong>Adult children driving conversations:</strong> A growing number of preneed purchases are initiated by adult children who want to help their aging parents plan ahead.</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				In North Carolina specifically, we're seeing this trend amplified by population growth. North Carolina gained over 1 million residents between 2010 and 2020, many of them transplants from higher-cost northeastern and midwestern states where preneed planning is already common. These families bring their expectations — and their willingness to plan — with them.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">NC HB 1003: New Preneed Law Changes</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				In 2025, the North Carolina General Assembly passed HB 1003, introducing several significant changes to preneed funeral regulations under N.C.G.S. Chapter 90, Article 13D. Funeral homes operating in North Carolina need to understand these changes:
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Trust-to-Insurance Conversion Provisions</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				HB 1003 includes provisions that facilitate the conversion of trust-funded preneed contracts to insurance-funded contracts. This is significant because insurance-funded preneed contracts offer several advantages: they're typically exempt from Medicaid spend-down, the growth is tax-deferred, and the death benefit can exceed the amount paid in — providing a hedge against funeral cost inflation.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				For funeral homes with existing trust-funded preneed portfolios, this creates an opportunity to restructure those contracts into a form that's more beneficial for both the funeral home and the consumer. However, the conversion process must comply with specific disclosure and consent requirements under the new law.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Religious Practices Accommodations</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The bill includes provisions addressing religious practices in funeral services, acknowledging the diverse faith traditions across North Carolina. This is particularly relevant for preneed planning, as it reinforces the importance of documenting religious preferences as part of the preneed contract.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Transportation Agreements</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				HB 1003 also addresses transportation agreements related to preneed contracts, clarifying the terms under which funeral homes can include transportation services in their preneed offerings. This is important for funeral homes serving rural areas where transportation logistics can be complex.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Digital Transformation of Preneed Sales</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The COVID-19 pandemic accelerated digital adoption across the funeral industry by five to ten years. Families who once expected an in-person kitchen-table conversation now routinely begin their preneed research online, compare options digitally, and expect the ability to start the process remotely.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				For funeral homes, this means that your digital presence is no longer optional — it's the front door to your preneed program. Funeral homes that invest in educational content, clear pricing information, and easy-to-use contact mechanisms will capture leads that would otherwise go to national competitors or, worse, to no one at all.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The data supports this shift. Online preneed inquiries have increased by approximately 35% since 2020. Families under 60 are significantly more likely to initiate preneed research online than through a walk-in or referral. And funeral homes with robust digital preneed content consistently outperform those without in lead generation.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				This doesn't mean the kitchen-table conversation is dead — far from it. The personal relationship remains the cornerstone of preneed sales. But the path to that conversation increasingly starts with a Google search, not a phone book listing.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">The Aging Boomer Wave: Projections Through 2035</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The demographic engine driving preneed growth is undeniable. The Baby Boomer generation — born between 1946 and 1964 — is entering the age range where preneed planning becomes most relevant. By 2030, every Boomer will be at least 66 years old. By 2035, the oldest Boomers will be approaching 90.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				For North Carolina specifically, the numbers are striking:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-6">
				<li><strong>North Carolina's 65+ population</strong> is projected to grow from approximately 1.9 million in 2025 to over 2.5 million by 2035 — a 30%+ increase.</li>
				
				<li>North Carolina is among the top destinations for retiree migration, further accelerating the aging of the population.</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				This wave will drive demand for both at-need and preneed services. Funeral homes that build strong preneed programs now are effectively pre-selling their services to this demographic wave — locking in revenue, building relationships, and reducing their dependence on at-need volume, which is inherently unpredictable.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The funeral homes that wait until the wave crests to invest in preneed will find themselves competing for market share that their more forward-thinking competitors have already captured.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">What Funeral Homes Should Do Now</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Based on the trends outlined above, here are the strategic priorities for funeral homes in North Carolina:
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">1. Invest in Your Preneed Program</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				If you don't have a dedicated preneed program, start one. If you have one that's been on autopilot, revitalize it. Preneed is not a side business — it's a strategic asset that smooths revenue, builds long-term client relationships, and compounds in value over time. Allocate budget, assign staff, and track performance with clear KPIs.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">2. Get Compliant with HB 1003</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Review your preneed contracts, disclosures, and processes against the new requirements. If you have trust-funded contracts that could benefit from conversion to insurance-funded, start evaluating the process now. Don't wait for a Board examination to discover compliance gaps.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">3. Train Your Staff</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Preneed sales require a different skill set than at-need services. Your staff needs to be comfortable initiating preneed conversations, handling objections, and guiding families through the planning process. Invest in training and, where appropriate, bring in experienced preneed professionals to supplement your team.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">4. Diversify Your Carriers</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Don't put all your eggs in one carrier basket. Work with a licensed preneed professional who represents multiple carriers and can match each family with the best available product. This protects your funeral home from carrier risk and improves outcomes for your families.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">5. Build Your Digital Presence</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Your website should do more than list your services. It should educate, build trust, and generate preneed leads. Invest in content that answers the questions families are asking: "How much does a funeral cost?" "What is preneed insurance?" "How do I plan ahead?" Every piece of content is an opportunity to start a relationship.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">6. Think Long-Term</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Every preneed policy sold today is a funeral service secured for the future. The funeral homes that build the largest preneed books over the next five to ten years will be the ones that thrive as the Boomer wave crests. This is a compounding game — start now.
			</p>

			<div class="bg-linen rounded-xl p-8 mt-12 border border-border-light">
				<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mb-3">Need Help With Your Preneed Program?</h2>
				<p class="text-charcoal-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
					I've spent nearly 20 years building preneed programs for funeral homes across North Carolina. Whether you need help with carrier selection, compliance, staff training, or program strategy, I'd welcome a conversation.
				</p>
				<p class="text-charcoal-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
					Call me directly at <a href="tel:9198222010" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 font-bold">{PHONE}</a> or visit the <a href="/for-funeral-homes" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">consulting services page</a> to learn more.
				</p>
				<p class="text-charcoal-500 text-sm">— Duane Cutlip, Licensed Preneed Funeral Director, North Carolina</p>
			</div>
		</article>
	</div>

	<CTABanner title="Let's Talk About Your Preneed Program" subtitle="Duane consults with funeral homes across North Carolina on preneed strategy, compliance, and growth." />
